\section*{INTRODUCTION TO HEALTH RECORDS MANAGEMENT}

The health record is a written collection of information about a patient. It originates from the patient's first encounter or treatment at a hospital, health post or other primary health care centre.

The health record is thus a record of all the procedures carried out on that patient, while he is in the hospital or under treatment at a clinic or centre. It should contain the past medical history of the patient, including opinions, investigations and other details relevant to the health of the patient.

You might also hear patients referred to as 'clients' in certain settings. Sometimes these words are used interchangeably.

As a document it may appear in many shapes and sizes with varied information related to the care of the patient recorded by many health care professionals in many ways. In physical appearance, it consists of a number of sheets of paper or cards and may be placed in a cover or envelope.

In more advanced health care facilities, the information may be recorded digitally in a computer; the sheets of paper scanned onto optical media or the actual sheets may be microfilmed. (Microfilming is similar to taking a picture of the paper and storing it on a film strip.)

Also through data entry on a database where they are different types of databases i.e. MySQL and access

Edna Huffman (1994), one of the first medical record professionals in the U.S., defined a health record as "a compilation of pertinent facts of a patient's life and health history, including past and present illness (es) and treatment(s), written by the health professionals contributing to that patient's care. The health record must be compiled in a timely manner and contain sufficient data to identify the patient, support the diagnosis, justify the treatment, and accurately document the results."

The actual physical record should be of an acceptable size and standardized on suitable forms, as far as possible to enable interchange of information, from hospital to hospital, hospital to health centre, hospital to general practitioner or other primary health worker.

The record must contain forms approved by the facility and the folder itself should be of a standard weight.

It is also important to note difference between a medical record and a health record
Medical record: it is a document created by a health profession concerning diagnostic procedures done on any client visiting the health facility

Examples:
- X-ray films,
- Temperature pulse respiration chart - filled by a nurse / clinician monitoring those elements above either four times per day or thrice,
- Cardiograph
- Encephalogram record
- C-T scan image (computer tomography image)

Health record: it is a general term referring to all documents created in a health facility concerning clients / patients visiting the health facility including:
- Counselling documentations
- Maternity records where the B1 are generated
- X-ray films

Point to note: all pregnant mothers attending check-ups clinics are not patients
This is where health professionals prefer to call all people visiting the health facility for one reason or another as a client before undergoing any diagnostic procedure for approval to be called a patient.

The hospital or facility health professionals assist in creating any health record by extracting information from clients thus the owner of information on a medical he or she is the client but the physical health record it is for the government, but in private hospitals it is for the hospital

\section*{HISTORICAL BACKGROUND OF HEALTH RECORDS DISCIPLINE}

\section*{Learning Objectives}

The learner should be able to:-
1. Define health records
2. Give a historical background of health records discipline
3. Define a health records department
4. Enumerate the functions of a health records and information department
5. Explain the various functions of a health records and information department

\section*{Definition:}

A health record is any written document about a patient in a professional relationship with a doctor.

It is a single repository data of a patient.

\section*{Historical Background}

The history of Health Records runs parallel with the history of medicine. Records are necessary for the practice of medicine as medications are for effective treatment, and they seem to have been made from earliest antiquity.

The first real physician of health records in Egypt is Imhotep. He lived in the pyramid age (about $3,000-2500 \mathrm{BC}$ ) and was grand vizier, chief architect, and royal medical adviser to a Pharaoh of the $29^{\text {th }}$ century before Christ. Imhotep has been credited with the authorship of the Edwin Smith Papyrus. This papyrus is one of the most valuable ancient medical documents that has come down to us and appears to have been copied about 1600 BC from an earlier original. This papyrus is a roll over 15 feet by about 3 inches wide and is made up of 12 sheets of the usual size. It is written on both sides and consists of 48 cases of Clinical Surgery.

It had information on conditions like gout and tumours

In Greece Hippocrates, known as the "father of medicine" was born about 460 BC. He was the first to cast out superstition and to practice medicine on scientific principles. He was the author of the Hippocratic Oath, which is pledged by physicians and which, states in part:
"Whatsoever in my practice or not in my practice, I shall see or hear amid the lives of men which ought not to be noised abroad- as to this I shall keep silence, holding such things unfitted to be spoken".

It was short but it captured many things that surround patient care information i.e. health records professional ethics, confidentiality, disclosure, security of patient information, ownership of a health record etc.

Thus originated the privacy of all information given to physicians by patients, eventually the Health Records per see was, also considered as privileged communication. Hippocrates kept detailed case reports of his patients.

In the $18{ }^{\text {th }}$ Century, Benjamin Franklin was one of the first leaders in the movement to establish the first incorporated hospital within the United States. This institution was known as Pennsylvania in 1751. Franklin served as secretary of the hospital, and many of its earliest records are in his handwriting.

In the $19{ }^{\text {th }}$ Century in 1821 the famous Massachusetts General Hospital Boston opened. Is has the distinction of having a complete file of clinical records, with all cases catalogued, dating from the day it opened.

In the $20^{\text {th }}$ Century, it was not until the beginning of this era that medical records received serious consideration by other types of hospitals and especially by hospitals and medical associations.

In 902 the American Hospital Association discussed Health Records for the first time at a convention.

In 1948 Health Records Association was started in Britain.
In 1967 the Department of Health Records was started in Kenya at Kenyatta National Hospital, Nairobi.

In 1978 the Health Records and Information Technician Program was started at the Medical Training College, Nairobi.

In 1990, the Health records and information officers program was started at the medical training college, Nairobi.

\section*{PURPOSE OF THE HEALTH RECORD}

As indicated above a good complete health record should encompass all information about a patient's health, ill health, treatment over a period of time and patient status at discharge. Health records are kept for:
- communication purposes
- continuity of patient care/ treatment
- evaluation of patient care
- monitoring and evaluation of health systems
- medico-legal purposes
- statistical purposes
- research
- Education.
- historical purposes

\section*{Communication purposes}

Health records are kept initially for communication between persons responsible for the care of the patients present and future needs. Many health professionals often see a patient. In a hospital the registration entails collection of identification information which also includes the patient's financial status. Only those people that actually treat the patient should document in the patient record. Some of these people include:
- consultants, physicians, surgeons, obstetricians
- nurses
- physiotherapist
- occupational therapists
- medical social workers
- laboratory technologists
- dieticians
- medical students
- Radiologists, etc.

Medical record staff will have access to the record to ensure that all documents are appropriately filed and organized and may also perform quality audits or research as requested by the facility or other agency.

\section*{Continuity of patient care / Treatment}

The patient may be readmitted to the same or another hospital or visit a clinic where all his past medical history should be available for assessment in the light of their current problem. It is vital that the primary health worker, who is responsible for the patient as a whole, should receive information about a patient's hospitalisation as soon as possible after the patient is discharged from hospital.

The main function of the health record department in a hospital or clinic, in this context, is as a service area, that is, medical records should be produced for patient care at all times and as quickly as possible. Also, discharge summaries and letters must be processed so that people outside the hospital may be informed of the patient's progress and their continued management after discharge.

\section*{Evaluation of patient care}

In any setting in which an individual puts the responsibility for their health and well-being into the hands of others, there should be some mechanism that enables evaluation of the standard of care being given. In some countries, hospital medicine is evaluated by an 'accreditation' system. Surveys of each hospital are made and hospitals given 'accreditation' by a Board for a limited number of years, depending on the standard which they reach. Also, in some countries, the health record services of a hospital must meet predetermined standards.
The health records is first and foremost of value in the present and future treatment of the patient.

\section*{Medico-legal}

Occasionally, health or medical records are used to substantiate substandard care and are then used to find justice and fair judgement in court rulings. This happens with regularity in the U.S., England and Australia, Kenya and others.

The record also, however, protects the patients by documenting all injuries and diseases or conditions in the record so that there is no confusion about what happened to the patient.

\section*{Statistical purposes}

Statistics are collected in hospitals, clinics and in primary health care centres. They may be used to tabulate numbers of diseases, surgical procedures and incidence of recovery after certain treatments; to assess areas which the hospital or clinic serves by collecting demographic details; or for public health or epidemiology. The morbidity and mortality statistics collected are used in planning health services activities, decision making, supply of drugs \& equipment ,staffing and day today running of the institutions.

\section*{Research}

In the past, accurate recording of observation in the health record would lead to accurate information required for research, but demographic and epidemiological information contained in the record is more often used today for purposes. The MOH (Ministry of Health) will use data reported from medical records through the current HMIS reporting structure to compare diseases and conditions across hospitals in the country and, in turn, will report data to the World Health Organization for comparisons throughout the world. The facility where the data is collected should also use the information to improve patient's care and also to monitor their progress closely for example:
- The cohort registers to monitor clients progress in quarters especially the HIV infected and HIV Exposed infants (HEI) ,
- Inpatient master index etc.

